      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/software-quality-assurance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "SQA: Version-controlled solver with documented validation suite",
        "description": "The CFD solver must be a commercially released or open-source code with documented version control, a regression test suite covering the relevant physics (turbulent incompressible flow, rotating reference frames), and a traceable release history. User-defined hemolysis power-law subroutines must be under configuration management with change logs."
      },
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2021 R2 was used under an FDA-licensed installation with documented version control. The solver ships with a validated turbomachinery regression suite (350+ test cases). The Giersiepen–Wurzinger hemolysis power-law UDF was maintained in a Git repository (commit SHA documented in the simulation archive). SQA procedures follow FDA 21 CFR Part 11 electronic records requirements. Achieved Gradation 2: solver identity, version, and UDF provenance are fully traceable."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/numerical-code-verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/numerical-code-verification",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Code verification: convergence to manufactured solution for rotating-frame Navier-Stokes",
        "description": "The solver must demonstrate formal order-of-accuracy convergence (within 10% of theoretical order) for the rotating reference frame Navier-Stokes equations using the method of manufactured solutions (MMS) on at least two mesh refinement levels. Residuals must converge to machine precision for steady laminar MMS cases."
      },
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2021 R2 code verification for rotating-frame incompressible flow was confirmed via the published ANSYS verification manual (cases VM-CFD-0042 and VM-CFD-0043), which demonstrate 2nd-order spatial convergence for velocity and pressure using MMS on structured and unstructured meshes. The hemolysis UDF was independently verified by comparing accumulated strain integral against an analytical solution for a Couette flow exposure scenario, yielding <0.5% error. Achieved Gradation 2: formal order-of-accuracy demonstration documented for the relevant equation set."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/discretization-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/discretization-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Discretization error: GCI_fine < 5% for hemolysis index and pressure head at all operating points",
        "description": "Richardson extrapolation on three systematically refined meshes (refinement ratio r ≥ 1.3) must yield a Grid Convergence Index for the fine mesh (GCI_fine) below 5% for the primary QoI (relative hemolysis index RH) and below 5% for pump pressure head ΔP at all five benchmark operating points. Observed order of convergence p_obs must be between 1.0 and 2.5."
      },
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was performed: coarse (1.2M cells), medium (4.8M cells), fine (19.2M cells), with refinement ratio r = 1.587. Richardson extrapolation yielded observed order p_obs = 1.91 (pressure head) and 1.78 (hemolysis index), both within the acceptable range. GCI_fine for RH: maximum 3.2% across all five operating points. GCI_fine for ΔP: maximum 2.4%. The fine mesh (19.2M cells) was selected for all production runs. Achieved Gradation 3: systematic three-level study with formal GCI quantification, exceeding the Gradation 2 requirement."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/test-conditions",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions: experimental boundary conditions documented with uncertainty; CFD BCs match within stated tolerances",
        "description": "Experimental test conditions (inlet flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature, hematocrit) must be documented with measurement uncertainty. CFD boundary conditions must be set to match experimental conditions within those stated uncertainties. Deviations between nominal CFD BCs and experimental means must be < 2% for flow rate and < 1% for rotational speed."
      },
      "rationale": "The FDA GCBP experimental dataset (Hariharan et al. 2011, Morrison et al. 2022) documents all test conditions with calibrated instrumentation: Coriolis flow meter (±0.5% FS), optical tachometer (±10 RPM), thermocouple (±0.5°C), and hematocrit centrifuge (±1% Hct). CFD boundary conditions were set to the mean experimental values for each of the five operating points. Maximum deviation between CFD BC and experimental mean: 0.8% (flow rate), 0.25% (speed). Fluid properties (viscosity, density) were set using measured temperature-dependent correlations. Achieved Gradation 2: all BCs documented with uncertainty and matched within tolerance."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/output-comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison: CFD predictions within combined uncertainty band of experimental measurements for all primary QoIs",
        "description": "CFD-predicted relative hemolysis index (RH) and pump pressure head (ΔP) must agree with experimental measurements within the combined expanded uncertainty (U_combined at 95% CI) at all five operating points. Agreement metric: (|CFD - Exp| / Exp) ≤ U_combined/Exp for each operating point."
      },
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison at all five operating points: RH agreement ranged from 2.1% to 9.4% relative error, all within the combined uncertainty band of ±11% (95% CI). Pressure head agreement ranged from 1.3% to 4.1% relative error, within the ±6% combined band. Velocity field NRMSE: 7.3%, within the 10% acceptance threshold. A validation uncertainty analysis following ASME V&V 20 was performed, separating numerical and experimental contributions. The model is declared validated for the purpose of identifying relative hemolysis ranking across operating points. Achieved Gradation 2: quantitative comparison with uncertainty analysis documented."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/relevance-qoi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/relevance-qoi",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance: hemolysis index and pressure head are clinically meaningful and directly linked to the COU decision",
        "description": "The primary QoI (relative hemolysis index RH) must be demonstrably linked to the clinical decision (identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions). A documented mapping from model output to decision criterion must exist. Secondary QoIs (ΔP, velocity field) must be shown to support the primary QoI assessment."
      },
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index RH is the direct clinical metric used to compare device hemolysis against a predicate device, as defined in FDA guidance on blood-contacting device submissions. The COU decision criterion (RH < 1.0 at worst-case operating point) is directly computed from the model's primary output. Pressure head and velocity field serve as intermediate validation QoIs that build confidence in the flow field prediction underlying the hemolysis calculation. The mapping from CFD shear stress history → power-law hemolysis model → RH is documented in the simulation protocol. Achieved Gradation 2: QoI relevance to COU decision is explicitly documented."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/relevance-validation-activities",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/relevance-validation-activities",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation relevance: validation experiments conducted on the same or geometrically similar device at overlapping operating conditions",
        "description": "Validation experiments must use the same FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry (or a certified replica) at operating conditions that overlap with or bracket the COU operating envelope. The validation dataset must include at least three of the five COU operating points. Fluid properties must match within ±10% of COU fluid properties."
      },
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted on certified replicas of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry manufactured to ISO 286 tolerances. All five COU operating points were included in the validation dataset. The validation fluid (porcine blood at 37°C, Hct 40%) closely matches COU fluid properties (human blood, Hct 35–45%). The validation activity was designed prospectively to cover the full COU operating envelope, not a post-hoc selection. Geometric fidelity of the pump replicas was confirmed by CMM measurement with all critical dimensions within ±0.05 mm of nominal. Achieved Gradation 2: validation activities directly relevant to COU geometry, conditions, and QoIs."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/numerical-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/numerical-solver-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Solver error: iterative convergence to residual < 1e-5 for all equations; mass imbalance < 0.01%",
        "description": "All steady-state RANS simulations must achieve scaled residual convergence below 1×10⁻⁵ for continuity, momentum, and turbulence equations. Global mass imbalance must be below 0.01%. Torque and pressure head monitors must show variation < 0.1% over the final 500 iterations."
      },
      "rationale": "All production simulations achieved scaled residuals below 5×10⁻⁶ for continuity and momentum, and below 1×10⁻⁶ for k and ω turbulence variables. Global mass imbalance: maximum 0.003% across all operating points. Pressure head and torque monitors converged to < 0.05% variation over the final 500 iterations. Double-precision arithmetic was used throughout. Iterative convergence was confirmed independent of mesh density (verified on all three mesh levels). Achieved Gradation 2: iterative convergence documented to required tolerance with monitoring data archived."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/use-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Use error: simulation protocol reviewed by independent analyst; setup files archived and reproducible",
        "description": "The simulation setup (mesh, boundary conditions, solver settings, UDF code) must be reviewed by an analyst independent of the original setup engineer. All simulation input files must be archived in a version-controlled repository enabling independent reproduction of results. At minimum, a checklist-based review must be documented."
      },
      "rationale": "An independent CFD analyst (not the original simulation engineer) performed a full review of the simulation setup files, boundary condition assignments, turbulence model selection, and UDF implementation prior to production runs. A structured review checklist (FDA-CDRH internal CFD review protocol v3.1) was completed and archived. All mesh files, case files, and UDF source code are stored in a version-controlled repository (Git, SHA documented). An independent reproduction of the 3 L/min / 3000 RPM operating point by the reviewer confirmed RH within 0.3% of the original result. Achieved Gradation 2: independent review with documented checklist, exceeding Gradation 1 requirement."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/model-form",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model form: turbulence model and hemolysis constitutive model selection justified with literature support",
        "description": "The choice of turbulence model (RANS closure) and hemolysis power-law model must be justified by reference to published benchmark studies on blood pump CFD. At least one sensitivity study comparing alternative turbulence models must be documented. The hemolysis model constants must be traceable to published experimental calibration data."
      },
      "rationale": "The SST k-ω turbulence model was selected based on its demonstrated superior performance for rotating machinery with adverse pressure gradients, as documented in the FDA GCBP inter-laboratory study (Stewart et al. 2012) and the ASME V&V 40 blood pump benchmark. A sensitivity study comparing SST k-ω against realizable k-ε showed < 8% difference in predicted RH at all operating points, with SST k-ω showing better agreement with PIV velocity measurements. The Giersiepen–Wurzinger hemolysis power-law constants (C = 3.62×10⁻⁷, α = 2.416, β = 0.785) are traceable to in vitro Couette flow calibration experiments (Giersiepen et al. 1990). Achieved Gradation 2: model form selection justified with comparative evidence and traceable constants."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/model-inputs",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model inputs: all fluid properties and geometric parameters documented with sources and uncertainty estimates",
        "description": "Blood viscosity (dynamic and apparent), density, and hematocrit must be documented with source references and uncertainty bounds. Pump geometry must be traceable to the FDA GCBP CAD specification with dimensional tolerances documented. Inlet velocity profile and turbulence intensity must be specified with justification."
      },
      "rationale": "Blood properties: dynamic viscosity modeled as Newtonian (μ = 0.0035 Pa·s ± 5%) based on Hct 40% at 37°C per Chien et al. (1966), density ρ = 1056 kg/m³ ± 0.5%. The Newtonian assumption is justified for the high-shear regions dominant in hemolysis at the operating speeds considered. Pump geometry was imported directly from the FDA GCBP CAD file (Rev. C, released 2012) with surface mesh quality verified (maximum skewness < 0.85, minimum orthogonality > 0.15). Inlet boundary: uniform velocity profile with turbulence intensity 5% and hydraulic diameter-based length scale, consistent with the upstream piping geometry. All input parameters tabulated in the simulation data package with provenance references. Achieved Gradation 2: all inputs documented with sources and uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/test-samples",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test samples: pump replicas manufactured to documented tolerances; blood samples from characterized donors",
        "description": "Physical pump replicas used in validation experiments must be manufactured to documented dimensional tolerances traceable to the FDA GCBP CAD specification. Blood samples (or blood analogues) must be from characterized donors or lots with documented hematocrit, viscosity, and storage conditions. At minimum, sample provenance must be documented."
      },
      "rationale": "Three pump replicas were manufactured by precision CNC machining from the FDA GCBP CAD specification. CMM inspection reports confirm all critical dimensions (impeller diameter, blade angles, volute clearance) within ±0.05 mm of nominal. Porcine blood was sourced from a single abattoir lot, processed within 4 hours of collection, and characterized for Hct (40 ± 1%), pH (7.35–7.45), and baseline plasma-free hemoglobin (< 5 mg/dL). Three independent experimental runs were performed per operating point using fresh blood from the same lot to assess inter-run variability. Sample traceability chain documented in the experimental data package. Achieved Gradation 2: sample provenance and characterization exceed Gradation 1 requirements."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/equivalency-input-parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/equivalency-input-parameters",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Equivalency: CFD input parameters match experimental conditions within stated measurement uncertainty for all five operating points",
        "description": "A parameter-by-parameter comparison between CFD simulation inputs and experimentally measured conditions must be documented for each operating point. Any systematic offset between CFD nominal and experimental mean must be within the experimental measurement uncertainty. Equivalency must be confirmed for flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature, and hematocrit."
      },
      "rationale": "A formal equivalency table was constructed comparing CFD input values against experimental measurements for all five operating points across four parameters: flow rate Q, rotational speed N, fluid temperature T, and hematocrit Hct. Maximum systematic offsets: ΔQ = 0.03 L/min (< 0.5% FS, within Coriolis meter uncertainty of ±0.5% FS), ΔN = 8 RPM (within tachometer uncertainty of ±10 RPM), ΔT = 0.3°C (within thermocouple uncertainty of ±0.5°C), ΔHct = 0.5% (within centrifuge uncertainty of ±1%). No parameter showed a systematic offset exceeding its measurement uncertainty. The equivalency table is archived in the validation data package and reviewed in the simulation report. Achieved Gradation 2: full parameter equivalency documented for all operating points."
    }
  ],
