    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (CPB hemolysis worst-case identification, Class II, MRL 2) is accepted based on the following structured evidence review. All 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed and all achievedLevel values meet or exceed the corresponding requiredLevel. Key evidence supporting acceptance: (1) Software quality assurance (Gradation 2): ANSYS Fluent 2021 R2 with version-controlled UDF and FDA 21 CFR Part 11 compliance confirmed. (2) Code verification (Gradation 2): formal MMS convergence demonstrated for rotating-frame Navier-Stokes. (3) Discretization error (Gradation 3, exceeding requirement): three-level mesh study with GCI_fine < 3.2% for primary QoI. (4) Test conditions (Gradation 2): experimental BCs documented with calibrated instrumentation, CFD BCs matched within measurement uncertainty. (5) Output comparison (Gradation 2): all five operating points within combined uncertainty band (±11% for RH, ±6% for ΔP). (6) QoI relevance (Gradation 2): RH directly linked to clinical decision criterion. (7) Validation relevance (Gradation 2): validation conducted on certified pump replicas at all five COU operating points. (8) Numerical solver error (Gradation 2): iterative convergence to < 5×10⁻⁶ residuals with < 0.003% mass imbalance. (9) Use error (Gradation 2): independent review with structured checklist and reproducibility confirmed. (10) Model form (Gradation 2): SST k-ω justified with comparative turbulence model sensitivity study. (11) Model inputs (Gradation 2): all fluid and geometric inputs documented with sources and uncertainty. (12) Test samples (Gradation 2): characterized porcine blood from traceable lot, three replicas with CMM inspection. (13) Equivalency of input parameters (Gradation 2): formal equivalency table confirms all parameters within measurement uncertainty. The sensitivity analysis demonstrates that hemolysis index predictions are robust to ±10% variation in viscosity and ±5% variation in pump geometry within the specified tolerance band. The decision is supported by complete provenance from foundational experimental data through validated simulation outputs to the clinical decision criterion. No shortfalls requiring offset rationale were identified. The model is fit for the stated purpose of identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for this Class II CPB device.",
